---

## Issues Found & Recommendations

### 1. Missing JSON Body Parser Middleware
The app has no `express.json()` or `express.urlencoded()` middleware. Any `POST`/`PUT` route added later won't parse request bodies at all.

```js
app.use(express.json({ limit: '10kb' })); // limit prevents payload bloat attacks
app.use(express.urlencoded({ extended: false, limit: '10kb' }));
```

### 2. No Input Validation on Query Parameters
The `/users` route doesn't validate query params (e.g., `?id=`, `?name=`). Any query-driven filtering should sanitize inputs to prevent injection.

### 3. No Global Error Handling Middleware
There's no catch-all error handler. Unhandled errors will expose stack traces or crash the process.

```js
// Add at the END, after all routes
app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  console.error(err.stack); // log internally, never expose to client
  res.status(err.status || 500).json({ error: 'Internal server error' });
});
```

### 4. No 404 Handler
Unknown routes silently fall through. Add a catch-all for unmatched routes:

```js
app.use((req, res) => {
  res.status(404).json({ error: 'Not found' });
});
```

### 5. Missing Security Headers
No HTTP security headers are set. Add the `helmet` package:

```js
const helmet = require('helmet');
app.use(helmet()); // sets X-Content-Type-Options, X-Frame-Options, HSTS, etc.
```

### 6. No Rate Limiting
The `/users` endpoint (and any future routes) are wide open to abuse. Add `express-rate-limit`:

```js
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');
const limiter = rateLimit({ windowMs: 15 * 60 * 1000, max: 100 });
app.use(limiter);
```

### 7. Hardcoded Port
`3000` is hardcoded. Use an environment variable so the port isn't baked into the binary:

```js
const PORT = process.env.PORT || 3000;
app.listen(PORT, () => console.log(`Server running on port ${PORT}`));
```

### 8. Sensitive Data in `/users` Response
Real apps should never return full user objects (especially emails or IDs) without authentication/authorization checks. Consider:
- Adding auth middleware before sensitive routes.
- Filtering/masking fields in responses.

---

## Improved Version

```js
const express = require('express');
const helmet = require('helmet');
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');

const app = express();
const PORT = process.env.PORT || 3000;

// Security headers
app.use(helmet());

// Body parsing with size limits
app.use(express.json({ limit: '10kb' }));
app.use(express.urlencoded({ extended: false, limit: '10kb' }));

// Rate limiting
const limiter = rateLimit({ windowMs: 15 * 60 * 1000, max: 100 });
app.use(limiter);

app.get('/health', (req, res) => {
  res.json({ status: 'ok', timestamp: new Date().toISOString() });
});

app.get('/users', (req, res, next) => {
  try {
    // TODO: add auth middleware and query param validation before production
    res.json([
      { id: 1, name: 'Alice', email: 'alice@example.com' },
      { id: 2, name: 'Bob', email: 'bob@example.com' },
    ]);
  } catch (err) {
    next(err); // forward to error handler
  }
});

// 404 handler
app.use((req, res) => {
  res.status(404).json({ error: 'Not found' });
});

// Global error handler — must have 4 args for Express to recognize it
app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  console.error(err.stack);
  res.status(err.status || 500).json({ error: 'Internal server error' });
});

app.listen(PORT, () => console.log(`Server running on port ${PORT}`));

module.exports = app;
```

